<h2>
    Top Local Rivers and Streams
</h2>
<h3>
    Tualatin River
</h3>
<p>
    Though not a premier trout river, certain cooler stretches and tributaries occasionally hold trout. It’s ideal for practicing casting or introducing beginners to moving water.
</p>
<h3>
    Trout Creek
</h3>
<p>
    A hidden gem for small stream fishing, especially for cutthroat trout. It's a bit of a drive from Beaverton but offers a peaceful, natural experience.
</p>
<h3>
    Upper Clackamas and Molalla Rivers
</h3>
<p>
    These rivers are about an hour from Beaverton but provide clear, cold water that trout love. Best for fly fishers targeting wild populations.
</p>
<h2>
    Best Lakes and Ponds for Stocked Trout
</h2>
<h3>
    Commonwealth Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Located in central Beaverton, this small lake is heavily stocked by ODFW in spring and fall. It’s perfect for beginners and families.
</p>
<h3>
    Henry Hagg Lake
</h3>
<p>
    A popular multi-species fishery just 25 minutes away. Hagg Lake is regularly stocked with rainbow trout and has several boat ramps and shore access points.
</p>
<h3>
    Bethany Lake &amp; Progress Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Great for after-work or weekend fishing trips. These urban lakes are stocked with trout multiple times per year and offer simple access for anglers of all levels.
</p>

